     = 51917\n| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\" />\n| population_est                  = 57738\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| population_density_km2          = 1488.77\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 3856.00\n| population_metro                = 720,042\n| population_density_metro_sq_mi  = <!-- General information  --------------->\n| population_note                 = \n| timezone                        = [[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = -5\n| timezone_DST                    = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -4\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->| postal_code_type                = ZIP code\n| postal_code                     = 34230\u201334243\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 941|941]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 12-64175<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = 0290675<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=US Board on Geographic Names |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.sarasotafl.gov}}\n}}\n\n'''Sarasota''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|s|\u00e6r|\u0259|\u02c8|s|o\u028a|t|\u0259}}) is a city in [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]] on the southwestern coast of the U.S. state of [[Florida]]. The area is renowned for its cultural and environmental amenities, beaches, resorts, and the [[Sarasota School of Architecture]]. The city is at the southern end of the [[Tampa Bay Area]], north of [[Fort Myers, Florida|Fort Myers]] and [[Punta Gorda, Florida|Punta Gorda]]. Its official limits include [[Sarasota Bay]] and several barrier islands between the bay and the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. According to the U.S. Census Bureau, in 2018 Sarasota had a population of 57,738. In 1986 it became designated as a certified local government. Sarasota is a principal city of the [[Sarasota metropolitan area]], and is the [[county seat|seat]] of Sarasota County.\n\nThe islands separating Sarasota Bay from the gulf near the city, known as [[Cay|keys]], include [[Lido Key]] and [[Siesta Key]], which are famous worldwide for the quality of their sandy [[beach]]es. The keys that are included in the boundary of Sarasota are [[Lido Key]], [[St. Armands Key]], Otter Key, Casey Key, Coon Key, [[Bird Key]], and portions of [[Siesta Key]]. Previously, Siesta Key was named Sarasota Key. At one time, it and all of [[Longboat Key]] were considered part of Sarasota and confusing contemporaneous references may be found discussing them.\n\nLongboat Key is the largest key separating the bay from the gulf, but it was evenly divided by the new county line of 1921. The portion of the key that parallels the Sarasota city boundary that extends to that new county line along the bay front of the mainland was removed from the city boundaries at the request of John Ringling in the mid-1920s, who sought to avoid city taxation of his planned developments at the southern tip of the key. Although they never were completed in the quickly faltering economy, those development concessions granted by the city never were reversed and the county has retained regulation of those lands.\n\nThe city limits had expanded significantly with the real estate rush of the early twentieth century, reaching almost {{convert|70|sqmi}}. The wild speculation boom began to crash in 1926 and following that, the city limits began to contract, shrinking to less than a quarter of that area.<ref>Cummings, Ian, [http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20140615/ARCHIVES/406151028/-1/todayspaper?p=2&tc=pg ''Razing near for city icon''], Sarasota Herald-Tribune, page BNV1, June 15, 2014</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Sarasota, Florida}}\n{{Further|Spanish Florida}}\n{{Expand section|1=a summary provided from [[History of Sarasota, Florida]]|section=1|date=August 2018|small=no|talksection=History of Sarasota, Florida}}\nThe area known today as Sarasota first appeared on a sheepskin Spanish map from 1763 with the word {{lang|es|Zarazote}} over present day Sarasota and [[Bradenton, Florida|Bradenton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Origin of the Name, Sarasota |url=http://www.sarasotahistoryalive.com/history/articles/the-origin-of-the-name-sarasota/ |website=Sarasota History Alive! |accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref> The municipal government of Sarasota was established when it was incorporated as a town in 1902.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sarasota History |url=http://historicpreservationsarasota.org/sarasotahistory/ |website=History & Preservation Coalition of Sarasota County |accessdate=August 22, 2018 |date=October 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Geography and climate ==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|25.9|sqmi|km2}}, of which {{convert|38.6|km2|abbr=on|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|11.0|sqmi|abbr=on}} is water.\n\nSarasota has a [[humid subtropical]] climate closely bordering a [[tropical savanna climate]], with hot, humid summers, and warm, dry winters. There are distinct rainy and dry seasons, with the rainy season lasting from June to September, and the dry season from October to May. The most recent officially recorded freezes in Sarasota took place on January 18, 2018, when the temperature dropped to {{convert|30|F}} at the Sarasota-Bradenton International Airport.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://w2.weather.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=tbw |title=NOWData \u2013 NOAA Online Weather Data |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |year=2019 |publisher=[[NOAA]]}}</ref> However, Sarasota averages less than one frost annually.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://w2.weather.gov/climate/index.php?wfo=tbw |title=Tampa Bay Area National Weather Service Climate Page |date=February 1, 2012 |accessdate=October 15, 2015 |website=Tampa Bay Area National Weather Service |publisher=National Weather Service |last=Cole |first=Brian}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = [[Sarasota\u2013Bradenton International Airport]] (1989\u20132018 normals, extremes 1911\u2013present)\n|single line = Y\n|temperature colour=\n|Jan record high F = 91\n|Feb record high F = 90\n|Mar record high F = 91\n|Apr record high F = 96\n|May record high F = 98\n|Jun record high F = 100\n|Jul record high F = 101\n|Aug record high F = 101\n|Sep record high F = 98\n|Oct record high F = 99\n|Nov record high F = 92\n|Dec record high F = 90\n|year record high F = 101\n|Jan high F = 71.3\n|Feb high F = 73.2\n|Mar high F = 76.3\n|Apr high F = 81.2\n|May high F = 86.1\n|Jun high F = 88.8\n|Jul high F = 89.9\n|Aug high F = 90.2\n|Sep high F = 89.0\n|Oct high F = 84.7\n|Nov high F = 78.3\n|Dec high F = 73.7\n|year high F = \n|Jan mean F = 61.9\n|Feb mean F = 63.9\n|Mar mean F = 67.1\n|Apr mean F = 72.0\n|May mean F = 77.3\n|Jun mean F = 81.1\n|Jul mean F = 82.5\n|Aug mean F = 82.7\n|Sep mean F = 81.4\n|Oct mean F = 76.2\n|Nov mean F = 68.9\n|Dec mean F = 64.4\n|Jan low F = 52.4\n|Feb low F = 54.6\n|Mar low F = 57.9\n|Apr low F = 62.7\n|May low F = 68.4\n|Jun low F = 73.4\n|Jul low F = 75.0\n|Aug low F = 75.2\n|Sep low F = 73.8\n|Oct low F = 67.7\n|Nov low F = 59.5\n|Dec low F = 55.2\n|year low F = 64.1\n|Jan record low F = 23\n|Feb record low F = 21\n|Mar record low F = 30\n|Apr record low F = 37\n|May record low F = 45\n|Jun record low F = 52\n|Jul record low F = 62\n|Aug record low F = 60\n|Sep record low F = 58\n|Oct record low F = 40\n|Nov record low F = 27\n|Dec record low F = 20\n|year record low F = 20\n|Jan avg record low F = 34.7\n|Feb avg record low F = 37.4\n|Mar